[[Image:Pavao Skalić; Enciklopedija ili znanje svijeta svetih i svjetovnih struka (1559).jpg|thumb|Title page of Skalich's  ''Encyclopaedia seu orbis disciplinarum tam sacrarum quam prophanarum epistemon'' from 1559, arguable one of the first encyclopedias to clearly use the word ''encyclopedia''in its title.<ref>{{cite book | last = Yeo | first = Richard | title = Encyclopaedic visions : scientific dictionaries and enlightenment culture | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge New York | year = 2001 | isbn = 978-0521152921 |page=6}}</ref>]]
{{italic title}}
'''''Encyclopediae seu orbis disciplinarum tam sacrarum quam profanarum epistemon''''' is an early encyclopedia written in Latin by [[Zagreb]] born philosopher [[Paul Skalic]]. It was first published in [[Basel]] in 1559<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sZdiAAAAMAAJ&q=Encyclopediae+seu+orbis+disciplinarum+tam+sacrarum+quam+profanarum+epistemon&dq=Encyclopediae+seu+orbis+disciplinarum+tam+sacrarum+quam+profanarum+epistemon&hl=en&ei=i-I8TNfBKOjGOIb8qKYP&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAQ|author=Franolić, Branko|title=
L'influence de la langue française en Croatie, d'après les mots empruntés: aspect socio-historique|publisher=Nouvelles éditions latines|year=1975|page=36}}</ref> and reprinted in [[Cologne]], Germany in 1571. It is often considered to be the first [[encyclopedia]] to use the term ''encyclopedia'' in its title.{{sfn|Yeo|2001|p=6}} This is not to be confused with the first appearance of the word which was disputed by [[Robert Collison]] who later reported that the work was poorly written, and that [[Joachim Sterck van Ringelbergh]] had used the word "cyclopaedia" to describe his work in 1541.{{fact|date=March 2018}}

