{{italic title}}
'''''Epistulae ad Brutum''''' ('''''Letters to Brutus''''') is a collection of letters between [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] politician and orator [[Cicero|Marcus Tullius Cicero]] and fellow politician, and conspirator against [[Julius Caesar]], [[Marcus Junius Brutus the Younger|Marcus Junius Brutus]]. The letters in this collection, when combined with Cicero's other letters, are considered some of the most reliable sources of information for the period leading up to the fall of the [[Roman Republic]].<ref name="eb1911-cicero">{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Cicero}}</ref> Cicero became acquainted with Brutus through his close friend [[Titus Pomponius Atticus]], an admirer of Brutus. Their personal relationship likely grew during their time together in opposition to Caesar during [[Caesar's Civil War|the civil war]] in 49&nbsp;BCE, it being firmly established by the time Cicero returned to Rome in the autumn of 47.<ref name="loeb-2002" />

Traditionally divided into two books, the collection features 26 letters written from March or April to July 43&nbsp;BCE — a year after the [[assassination of Julius Caesar]], and a year before the death of Brutus in 42. The authenticity of the letters was for a long time cast into doubt, but is now generally recognized, with the exception of the first book's letters 16 and 17.<ref name="loeb-2002">{{Cite book |editor-last=Shackleton Bailey |editor-first=D. R. |editor-link=D. R. Shackleton Bailey |date=May 2002 |title=Letters to Quintus and Brutus. Letter Fragments. Letter to Octavian. Invectives. Handbook of Electioneering |url=http://www.loebclassics.com/view/LCL462/2002/volume.xml |publisher=Harvard University Press |access-date=5 October 2015}}</ref> These two letters resemble the style of ''{{lang|la|suasoriae}}'' — exercises in [[rhetoric]] commonly used by students of the late [[Roman Republic|Republic]] and [[Augustus|Augustan]] eras. The second book of Cicero's letters to Brutus was first printed by [[Andreas Cratander]] of [[Basel]] in 1528 from a now lost manuscript obtained for him by [[Sichardus]] from the [[Lorsch Abbey|Abbey of Lorsch]].<ref name="eb1911-cicero" />

